  "prompt": "What is a zero sum game?",
  "response": "A zero-sum game is a situation in game theory where the total gains and losses among participants equal zero. In other words, one player's gain is exactly balanced by the losses of other players. This means that the resources or benefits are fixed, and any advantage gained by one participant comes at the expense of another.\n\nFor example, in a simple game of poker, the amount of money won by one player is equal to the amount lost by the other players. Therefore, the sum of the winnings and losses is zero. Zero-sum games are often used to model competitive situations where the interests of the players are directly opposed. \n\nIn contrast, non-zero-sum games allow for scenarios where all players can benefit or suffer simultaneously, leading to outcomes where the total gains and losses do not necessarily cancel each other out.",
